text: "A patient following a crush injury is passing red color urine due to myoglobinuria. Which of the following will most likely be seen in this patient?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Hypercalcemia", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "Hypomagnesemia", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Hypophosphatemia", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "D", "text": "Hyperkalemia", "is_correct": true}],
explanation: "**Crush injury**\n\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 **\u2193**\n**Muscle cell breakdown**\n\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 **\u2193**\n**Release of intracellular contents**\n\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 **\u2193**\n**Myoglobin + K\u207a + phosphate**\n\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 **\u2193**\n**Electrolyte imbalance + renal damage**\nCorrect answer is D because crush injury causes rhabdomyolysis with release of intracellular potassium from damaged muscle cells, leading to hyperkalemia.\nCell lysis\n\u00a0\u00a0 \u2193\nK\u207a released into blood\n\u00a0\u00a0 \u2193\nHyperkalemia\n\u00a0\u00a0 \u2193\nRisk of arrhythmias \u26a0\ufe0f\nMyoglobinuria is associated with acute kidney injury and electrolyte disturbances, especially life-threatening hyperkalemia.\nEarly phase typically shows hyperkalemia, hyperphosphatemia, and hypocalcemia, not hypercalcemia or hypophosphatemia.<br><br>| **Electrolyte** | **Change** |\n| ----------- | ------ |\n| **K\u207a** | \u2191 |\n| **Phosphate** | \u2191 |\n| Calcium | \u2193 (early), \u2191 (late) |",
