category: "Hematology",
subcategory: "01-rbc-disorders",
tags: ["PYQ", "FMGE Jul 2025"],
text: "A school going child is being evaluated for underperformance in school and reduced hemoglobin levels. He has history of eating wall paint for past few weeks. Which of the following is the likely cause of anemia observed in him?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Megaloblastic anemia", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "Thalassemia minor", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Sideroblastic anemia", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "D", "text": "Iron deficiency anemia", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "* Correct answer is C because pica with paint ingestion suggests lead exposure, which inhibits heme synthesis enzymes (ALA dehydratase and ferrochelatase) leading to acquired sideroblastic anemia.\n    This results in defective heme formation despite adequate iron availability.\n    Iron deficiency anemia is due to low iron stores. Megaloblastic anemia is due to B12/folate deficiency. Thalassemia minor is a globin chain synthesis defect.\n    \u00a0<br><br>    | **Feature** | **IDA** | **Sideroblastic** |\n    | ------- | --- | ------------- |\n    | Iron | \u2193 | \u2191 |\n    | Ferritin | \u2193 | \u2191 |\n    | Cause | Deficiency | Defective utilization |\n    | Smear | Hypochromic | Stippling |",
