id: "991192890ce32fc8",
category: "Hematology",
subcategory: "01-rbc-disorders",
tags: ["PYQ", "FMGE Jul 2025"],
text: "A female patient presents with iron deficiency anemia, dysphagia, and glossitis. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Achalasia cardia", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "Dysphagia lusoria", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Plummer Vinson syndrome", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "D", "text": "Carcinoma of the esophagus", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "Correct answer is C because Plummer\u2013Vinson syndrome is characterized by the triad of iron deficiency anemia, dysphagia due to esophageal webs, and glossitis.<br><br>| **Feature** | **Explanation** |\n| ------- | ----------- |\n| Iron deficiency anemia | \u2193 Hb |\n| Dysphagia | Esophageal web |\n| Glossitis | Mucosal atrophy |<br><br>\u00a0<br><br>* **Premalignant condition**<br><br>\u00a0Risk of: Squamous cell carcinoma\nIt is classically seen in middle-aged females and is associated with increased risk of upper esophageal squamous cell carcinoma.\nAchalasia causes dysphagia without iron deficiency anemia. Dysphagia lusoria is due to vascular compression. Esophageal carcinoma presents with progressive dysphagia and weight loss.<br><br>| **Feature** | **PVS** | **Carcinoma** |\n| ------- | --- | --------- |\n| Dysphagia | Intermittent | Progressive |\n| Iron deficiency | \u2705 | \u274c |\n| Glossitis | \u2705 | \u274c |\n| Cancer risk | Increased | \u2014 |",
