subcategory: "01-rbc-disorders",
tags: ["Path_Images"],
text: "A 5-year-old boy is brought to the clinic for a routine health maintenance examination. He underwent a splenectomy a year ago for persistent anemia and jaundice. He has received the pneumococcal and meningococcal vaccinations and takes penicillin prophylaxis. Physical examination reveals a well-appearing child. The sclerae are anicteric. The abdomen is soft and nontender; no masses are palpable. Several well-healed laparoscopy scars are noted. Complete blood count is as follows: \nHemoglobin: 11.3 g/dL\nReticulocytes: 3%\nPlatelets: 160,000/mm\u00b3\nLeukocytes: 8,200/mm\u00b3\nPeripheral blood smear with Wright stain is shown.\nThis patient's findings are most likely related to which of the following?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Chronic Hb oxidation and precipitation", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "Inability to produce beta globin chains", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Mechanical red-blood-cell membrane damage", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "D", "text": "Persistence of red blood cell precursor nuclei", "is_correct": true}],
explanation: "Howell\u2013Jolly bodies (basophilic nuclear remnants in RBCs) occur due to persistence of red blood cell precursor nuclei and are normally removed by the spleen.\nThey are seen in:<br><br>* Post-splenectomy states\n* Functional asplenia (e.g., sickle cell disease)<br><br>Severe hemolytic anemia",
