text: "A patient with a history of road traffic accident (RTA) presents with massive blood loss and has been transfused with 4 units of packed red blood cells within a few hours. Which of the following electrolyte abnormalities is most likely to occur?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Hypernatremia", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "Hypocalcemia", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "C", "text": "Hyperkalemia", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "D", "text": "Hyponatremia", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "Massive transfusion delivers citrate from stored blood, which chelates ionized calcium in the circulation. This reduces free Ca\u00b2\u207a and leads to transfusion-related hypocalcemia. Low calcium leads to:<br><br>* Neuromuscular irritability\n* Tetany\n* Cardiac arrhythmias<br><br>Rapid transfusion increases the risk because citrate metabolism is overwhelmed. The key electrolyte complication of massive transfusion is hypocalcemia.<br><br>| **Complication** | **Mechanism** |\n| ------------ | --------- |\n| \u00a0**Hypocalcemia** | Citrate binds Ca\u00b2\u207a |\n| Hyperkalemia | RBC lysis \u2192 K\u207a release |\n| Hypothermia | Cold blood transfusion |\n| Coagulopathy | Dilution of clotting factors |",
